===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|cortine}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|cortina}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|kû(r)'tən}}, {{IPA|/ˈkɜː(r)tən/}}, {{SAMPA|/"k3:(r)t@n/}}
* {{audio|en-us-curtain.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|En-uk-curtain.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|ɜː(r)tən}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A piece of [[cloth]] [[cover]]ing a [[window]] to keep the [[sun]] from shining inside.
# A similar piece of cloth that separates the [[audience]] and the [[stage]] in a [[theater]].
# {{context|fortifications}} The flat area of [[wall]] which connects two [[bastions]] or [[towers]]; the main area of a fortified wall.
#* '''1603''', John Florio, translating Michel de Montaigne, ''Essays'', Folio Society 2006, vol. 1, p. 220:
#*: Captain ''Rense'', beleagring the Citie of ''Errona'' for us, [...] caused a forcible mine to be wrought under a great '''curtine''' of the walles [...].

